  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Gender mainstreaming in social Accountability Phase 2</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The situation we are trying to change is; very high rate of exclusion of women from governance and decision making in Kogi State. Women in Kogi State make up 51% of the State population but hold only 7% of the elective and appointive leadership positions in the state. Also, women are excluded from decision making in the state. This inequitable and lopsided situation is the crux of the Gender Mainstreaming in Social Accountability Project (GEMISA) which CWSI initiated in the year 2014. Basically, the GEMISA intervention is aimed at strengthening women&#x2019;s political participation and increasing women&#x2019;s representation in decision making.

How we intended to change the situation:
The GEMISA Project gave birth to the formation of Kogi Women Empowerment Coalition (KWEC). The coalition has become a strong voice for Kogi women&#x2019;s struggle for gender inclusive governance. How we intend to change the situation is to further and better strengthen the capacity of KWEC to:
- Engage duty bearers, stakeholders and influential personalities and thus pressurize the human and structural barriers against women representation to care in. 
- Leverage on the large number of KWEC membership to mobilize community support for women political aspirants. 
- Improve the knowledge of women political aspirants, on the politics of politics, mapping and scanning of political environment for strategic advantage, building self-confidence, positive motivation, forming strong linkages and support, sharpening electioneering and public speaking skills as well as access to mentorship and creating financial capability.
- Create visibility for KWEC and women politicians through dedicated media outreaches.
- Passage of gender and equal opportunity law.  

CWSI envisages that using the above strategies to strengthen women&#x2019;s participation in political processes will enable the breaking down of societal, political and structural obstacles to women&#x2019;s political representation.</narrative>
  </description>
